    <name>
				<text>10.3.4.4 Cartesian form to exponential form (NOT IN QUIZ)</text>
		</name>
    <questiontext format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<p class="HELM_exercise">Exercise</p>
<p>Find the exponential form of the complex number \(z = \displaystyle {@re@} + \displaystyle \left({@im@}\right)i\). Give the argument of \(z\) in terms of \(\pi\), i.e. not in decimal form.</p>
<p>\(z =\quad\)[[input:ans1]][[validation:ans1]][[feedback:prt1]]</p>
<p>Therefore, find the Cartesian form of \(z^{-1}\). Give your answers in decimal form, rounding to 3 decimal places if necessary:</p>
<p>\(z^{-1} =\quad\)[[input:ans2]][[validation:ans2]]\(\quad+\quad i\) [[input:ans3]][[validation:ans3]]</p>
[[feedback:prt2]]]]></text>
		</questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<p> We want to calculate \(z\) in the form \(re^{i\theta}\). We calculate \(\displaystyle{r = \sqrt{\left({@re@}\right)^2 + \left({@im@}\right)^2} = {@arr@}}\) and \(\displaystyle{ \theta = \tan^{-1}\left({@im@}/{@re@}\right) = {@th@} }\). Therefore \[z = {@arr@}e^{{@th@}i}.\] To calculate the inverse, \(z^{-1}\),
    in Cartesian form we use laws of indices and then apply a Key Point from this workbook: \[z^{-1} = {@ta1@}^{-1} = {@arr@}^{-1}e^{-i({@th@})} = \dfrac{1}{{@arr@}}\left(\cos\left(-{@th@}\right) + i\sin\left(-{@th@}\right)\right) = {@ta2@} + {@ta3@}i.\]</p>]]></text>
		</generalfeedback>
